<td><font color="#eeeeee">Cellar</font><font color="#eeeeee">.</font>
<tr>
<td><font color="#eeeeee">up:</font>
<td><font color="#eeeeee">Hall</font><font color="#eeeeee">.</font>
<tr>
<td><font color="#eeeeee">down:</font>
<td><font color="#eeeeee">Cellar</font><font color="#eeeeee">.</font>
<tr>
<td><font color="#eeeeee">out:</font>
<td><font color="#eeeeee">Hall</font><font color="#eeeeee">.</font>
<tr>
<td><font color="#eeeeee">swampward:</font>
<td><font color="#eeeeee">Hall</font><font color="#eeeeee">.</font>
</table>
</td></tr></table>
</center>
</font>
<p>
To balance the stairs going <b>up</b> from the hall, I'll change the line
to the steps <b>down</b> to match, even though it is actually in the right
compass direction (it's the aesthete in me). This gives:
<p>
<center>
<table cellpadding="8" border="2"><tr><td bgcolor="white">
<img
 src="issue/15/images/map7.jpg">
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
I think you must be getting the idea now. Continuing into the cellar, we
get a door to the coal bunker in the west, am exit to a small tunnel
(dark) to the south and the steps back up to the northeast. I'll put the
small tunnel as the start of a separate area, but you could include them
(and their destination) as part of the cottage area if you liked.
<p>
With the ground floor and basement mapped, our draft looks like this:
<p>
<center>
<table cellpadding="8" border="2"><tr><td bgcolor="white">
<img
 src="issue/15/images/map8.jpg">
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
OK, that's probably enough to have got over the techniques involved! For
completeness, the full map of the cottage is presented
<span class="missing">here</span> (it's separate because you may decide you'd
rather make your own to compare with it; besides, it's quite big - 139K!).
If you do want to make your own, expect problems with the connection to
the attic :-) . You may also need to move the contents of rooms around a
bit to fit things together neatly.
<p>
<div align="center"><img src="icon/default.gif" alt="*"></div>
<p>
I hope this article has been of some help to people interested in making
their own maps. I also hope it hasn't put anyone off! I stress, yet again,
that maps are <i>individual</i> to the people who make them. What I want in
a map, you may not want; what I find intuitive, you may find nonsense. Do
your maps how <i>you</i> want to do them. You're the only person who'll see
them, so why worry what anyone else will think?
<p>
Remember that the game changes. I recently had to alter my
<a href="article.fod_IssueId_9_ArticleId_1199">overview map</a> so it accounted for the new
giants area. Although changes are rarely made to long-standing rooms, they
do occasionally happen so don't forget to alter your maps when you find an
anomaly. Otherwise, when you finally get around to trying the woodnymph
task, you may find yourself losing valuable time figuring out how you got
lost!
<p>
<div align="center"><img src="icon/default.gif" alt="*"></div>
<p>
<b><big>Further Reading</b></big>
<p>
You can produce pretty maps from your eyesore originals using the tools
available at the
<a href="http://ifarchive.org/indexes/if-archiveXmapping-tools.html">interactive
fiction archive</a>. They're meant for single-player adventure games, but
they're good for MUDs too.
<p>
<div align="center"><img src="icon/default.gif" alt="*"></div>
<p>
<b><big>Exercises</b></big>
<p>
Here are some exercises for you to put your mapping skills to practice
with. They're in sort of easiest-first order.
<p>
<ol>
<li>Discover which connection between the
&quot;<font color="#00ee00">Beaten track near cliff</font>&quot; and the
&quot;<font color="#00ee00">Cliff</font>&quot; itself are bidirectional.
(The &quot;<font color="#00ee00">Beaten track near cliff</font>&quot; is at
the westernmost end of the road).
<li>Use <b>qn</b> to find objects in the
&quot;<font color="#00ee00">Dense forest</font>&quot; rooms that surround
the misty graveyard <b>north</b> of the cottage. Don't worry if you can't
find any - other people may have taken them.
<li><b>w.s</b> from the treacherous swamp is the
&quot;<font color="#00ee00">Magical glade</font>&quot;. Here is an incomplete
map of it.
<p>
<center>
<table cellpadding="8" border="2"><tr><td bgcolor="white">
<img
 src="issue/15/images/glade.jpg">
</td></tr></table>
</center>
<p>
Fill in the blank boxes, removing those for directions that don't lead
to rooms.
<li>Draft a map for the room &quot;<font color="#00ee00">Valley
between mountains</font>&quot;. This room can be found by going
<b>w...nw</b> from the &quot;<font color="#00ee00">Ford in river</font>&quot;.
<li>Draft a map for the &quot;<font color="#00ee00">Rough heath</font>&quot;
which is <b>north</b> from
&quot;<font color="#00ee00">Valley between mountains</font>&quot;.
<li>Combine the two maps you have just created into one. Make sure you
match the right &quot;<font color="#00ee00">Middle mountain</font>&quot; and
&quot;<font color="#00ee00">Foothills</font>&quot; rooms together.
<li> Warning: you need a light source for this one.<br>
<b>w..s..</b> from the &quot;<font color="#00ee00">Ford in river</font>&quot;
takes you to some &quot;<font color="#00ee00">Inn steps</font>&quot;. Find
a sequence of directions which gets you from here to the
&quot;<font color="#00ee00">East part of attic</font>&quot; in the inn.
<li>Map the &quot;<font color="#00ee00">Small tunnel</font>&quot; rooms off of
the &quot;<font color="#00ee00">Cellar</font>&quot; and their connection
to the surface at their other end.
<li>Map the misty graveyard. This isn't as hard as you might think!
<li>Map the maze of hedges. Note that there <i>is</i> a map of this hidden
in the game somewhere, but it's not accurate enough to use. It is, though,
accurate enough to give you the general layout so your own map doesn't
sprawl across 20 sheets of paper.
</ol>
<p>
<div align="center"><img src="icon/default.gif" alt="*"></div>
